choices.text:
undeniably the end of the 200 year old absolute monarchy in 2010. But this was quickly followed by some criticism from within and outside from concerned scholars and observers that despite all the excited talk on reform, many aspects of the previous institution were kept in place undisturbed or with little change. One of such aspects was the convective monarchy with direct family ties. A responsible person was pointing out that this ‘revolving door’ meant a deliberate extra chain in the 'line of succession' and that this was counter-factual with the democratic aspirations of the era. It still reminds of the question: Is this really progress in any sense of the word?

“The move, from Monarch to Prime Minister, is historic and symbolic for the country. The constitution was written in the 1980s during the party system where it was assumed that the decisions about the country would come from the politicians. But our Constitution, when I read it carefully, it says that there is a multi party system. So basically, in Tonga every time the government changes, it is the parliament or politicians who make the decisions for the country. The people are in the board room making, putting their issues but is not significant in the real decisions for the country.

For Ha’apai, the decision to pursue domination by the monarchy was much more pragmatic and sensible given the islands’ civil divisions and stratification as well. The political struggle had long destroyed any sense of national identity or sovereignty in Ha’
